          "body": "Verse 15 is the theological summit of Isaiah 57 and one of the most compressed statements of divine character in the entire Old Testament. God describes Himself with four stacked phrases: high (*rum*), exalted (*nasa*), inhabiting eternity (*ad*), Holy (*qadosh*). The accumulation is intentional — each descriptor pushes God's transcendence further. Then the surprise: this same God says He dwells (*shakhan* — the tabernacle word) with the contrite (*dakka*, crushed, pulverized) and lowly of spirit (*shaphal ruach*). The juxtaposition is not resolved; it is stated in its full paradox. The God who is maximally transcendent is simultaneously maximally immanent — but He chooses His point of immanence deliberately. Not with the strong, not with the proud, not with the successful idolater on his high mountain. With the crushed. The purpose is stated: to revive (*chayah*) the spirit of the lowly and to revive the heart of the contrite. His co-habitation is not positional only; it is life-giving. His presence is the mechanism of their revival. Calvin saw in this verse the whole logic of grace: the more we see our own poverty, the more room there is for God."
